m a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":21,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William de Berdewell was born in 1361, in Bardwell, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of William de Berdewell and Berdewell. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Margaret de Pakenham. He died on 27 October 1434, in Suffolk, England, at the age of 73, and was buried in Bardwell, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1361–27 October 1434":"1361–27. oktoober 1434","1361–1434":"1361–1434","1367–1437":"1367–1437","1383–1428":"1383–1428","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1341–Male":"1341–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1437":"1437","1434":"1434","1400":"1400","